  I study how to regulate firms' access to consumer data when it is used for
price discrimination and the regulator possesses non-Bayesian uncertainty about
the correlation structure between data and willingness to pay. Therefore, it is
unclear how the monopolist will segment the market. I characterize all policies
that maximize worst-case consumer surplus: the regulator allows the monopolist
to access data, if the database does not reveal a minority group of consumers.
